---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="tracelane — live demo report">
  <h1>Live demo report</h1>
  <p class="tagline">A real tracelane <code>.html</code>, exactly as it lands on a CI runner's filesystem when a test fails.</p>

  <p>
    The link below opens an actual tracelane report &mdash; the same artifact your suite
    writes to <code>./tracelane-reports/</code> when a test fails. It contains the rrweb
    event stream, the inlined player, the console panel, and the failed-network panel.
    Fully offline. No server. No backend call.
  </p>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="cta" href="/demo/login-failure.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
      Open the demo report &rarr;
    </a>
  </div>

  <h2>What you're looking at</h2>

  <p>
    This report was generated by tracelane's own <code>e2e/smoke.e2e.ts</code> &mdash; a
    deliberately-failing WebdriverIO test against a static fixture. Real rrweb capture,
    real failure stack, real-time playback. The only post-processing on this file was
    redacting the absolute filesystem path of the test author's machine. Nothing else.
  </p>

  <h3>Try the player</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Scrub the timeline</strong> at the bottom &mdash; drag the playhead to any
    point in the test run. The DOM rewinds with you.</li>
    <li><strong>Click the speed control</strong> (lower-left of the player). Speed up for
    long-running setups; slow down to spot the exact frame a regression appeared.</li>
    <li><strong>Open the Console panel</strong> on the right. Every <code>console.*</code>
    call from the page is in there, with stack traces.</li>
    <li><strong>Open the Network panel</strong>. Failed responses (status &ge; 400) and
    network errors are surfaced with the request URL and any error text.</li>
    <li><strong>Hit the &ldquo;Copy as Markdown for AI&rdquo; button</strong> in the
    metadata header. It serialises the report's essential context into a clipboard-ready
    block you can paste into Claude Code / Cursor / Cline for AI-assisted debugging.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why this matters as a launch artifact</h2>
  <p>
    A demo URL beats a video. You can pause, scrub, inspect, replay &mdash; the same things
    you would do on your own bug ticket. This page exists because someone evaluating
    tracelane should be able to <em>see what an actual report looks like</em> in 30 seconds,
    without installing anything.
  </p>

  <h2>Get the real thing into your CI</h2>
  <p>
    Inside a WebdriverIO project, one command wires the Service + creates the reports
    directory + ignores it in git:
  </p>
  <pre><code>cd your-wdio-project
npx tracelane init</code></pre>

  <p>Or wire it by hand &mdash; see <a href="/getting-started">Getting started</a>.</p>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="cta" href="/getting-started">Getting started &rarr;</a>
    <a class="cta secondary" href="https://github.com/Cubenest/rrweb-stack/tree/main/packages/tracelane-wdio" rel="noopener">View on GitHub</a>
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
    The demo report file is ~159 KB. It loads instantly because all assets are inlined
    &mdash; same constraint your shipped reports operate under (25 MB cap, FullSnapshot
    preserved on overflow).
  </p>
</Layout>
